From b83d25e5828bb1314bc1d2545bdc44107bafb6be Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Sun, 19 Jul 2026 14:24:18 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fix: stop Venus validating founder's proposed number instead
 of comparing it
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Two root causes found in groq.ts/ai.ts, both reproducing the exact
sycophancy pattern reported (price/equity/budget asks get rubber-stamped,
follow-ups flip the verdict to match the newest number):

1. inferDecisionRouting classified any single proposed number with no
   explicit 'or'/'vs' as subtype 'binary', which routed to an explicit
   instruction to just give a verdict on the one stated path. Added a
   'single-value-benchmark' subtype: a number inside a benchmarkable
   category (pricing, equity/valuation, budget/allocation, etc.) now
   forces Venus to silently generate 2 realistic alternatives and score
   all of them via the existing decision-card format before recommending
   anything — agreement with the founder's number has to be earned by
   the comparison, not assumed.

2. Nothing caught same-session flip-flopping: retrieveOwnResolvedDecisions
   only surfaces a decision once an outcome is reported back (status
   'resolved'), so a decision Venus made 90 seconds ago in the same live
   conversation was invisible to the next turn. Added
   retrieveOpenSessionDecisions, scoped to open decisions from the last
   45 minutes of this session, injected as an 'OPEN RECOMMENDATIONS
   EARLIER THIS SESSION' block with a new system-prompt rule requiring
   explicit reconciliation instead of a silent fresh verdict.

Verified against the reported examples: 'shld i price at 500rs' and the
1cr budget-split question both now correctly route to
single-value-benchmark; the VC follow-up ('why not 1cr for 5%') doesn't
match any per-message regex (as expected — no per-message heuristic
can), which is exactly the case fix #2 exists to catch via session
history instead. typecheck:libs and api-server typecheck both pass
clean. Pre-existing note: groq.prompt.test.mjs was already failing
before this change (asserts phrases from an older prompt revision) —
unrelated to this patch, flagging separately.
